[See URL above for infographic aimed at college students depicting symptoms of mumps and steps they can take to protect themselves.]

[Research using mumps vaccine effectiveness data and dynamic transmission modeling from Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health shows the increase in mumps in college age students is likely because protection can decline years after receiving the vaccine. While it is expected that 50 percent of people will retain protection for 19 years after receiving a mumps-containing vaccine, many people will maintain protection far longer, so the population average is about 27 years," according to J Lewnard, Research Associate, Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health. The vaccine is nearly 90 percent effective after 2 doses, but a 3rd booster dose has been used to cut down on future cases, either in response to outbreaks or to prevent outbreaks.
(Lewnard JA and Grad YH. Vaccine waning and mumps re-emergence in the United States. Science Translational Medicine 21 Mar 2018: Vol. 10, Issue 433, eaao5945 DOI: 10.1126/scitranslmed.aao5945). - Mod.LK]

